_:e6048a2d50ba72b225d0ecfc4783be9e a <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/E52_Time-span> ;
	<http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P78_is_identified_by> "5th / 9th century (d. 478 / 1085)He was connected with the school of ʿilm al-kalām inaugurated by Abū al-Ḥasan al-Ašʿarī at the beginning of the 4th/10th century. But ʿAmīd al-Mulk al-Kundurī, vizier of the Salǧūq Tuġrul Beg, declared himself against this “innovation”, and had the Ašʿarīs, as well as the Rawāfiḍ, denounced from the pulpits. Al-Ǧuwaynī, like Abū al-Qāsim al-Qušayrī, immediately left his country and went to Baġdād; then, in 450/1058, he reached the Ḥiǧāz where he taught at Mecca and at Medina for four years: hence his honorary name of “Imām of the two holy Cities”. But when the vizier Niẓām al-Mulk came to power in the Salǧūq empire, he favoured the Ašʿarīs and invited the emigrants to return home.\n               " .
<https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS0061IHA> <http://www.cidoc-crm.org/cidoc-crm/P4_has_time_span> _:e6048a2d50ba72b225d0ecfc4783be9e .
